GSU: Lower Chehalis: Skook to Black SB
Percent conversion by 2040: 1) Portion of Grand Mound UGA within GSU is already industrial (gravel mine). In Centralia UGA portion of GSU, conversion anticipated to be 70% to urban residential densities (55% from forest, 15% from bare ground/rural densities/possible former ag fields) and the remaining 30% of the UGA projected to convert from fields/floodplain to industrial. 2) Outside of UGAs, the vast majority of the GSU is in Thurston County & zoned long term ag or within the boundaries of the Confederated Tribes of the Chehalis Reservation; no significant change anticipated.
General Notes: GSU includes primarily Centralia UGA, and small portion of Grand Mound UGA/area along I-5. GSU expands west along Hwy 12 from Rochester into Grays Harbor County in the Oakville area. Assume UGAs will build out at 100%. Most of Thurston County portion has already been converted from ag or forest to suburban/rural uses. Residential densities are anticipated to increase.
Note from NLCD classes: High density > 90% impervious, medium is 50-79%, low is 20-49%. I used 0.95 for HD, 0.65 for MD and 0.35 for LD.

Percent conversion by 2040: 1) No changes anticipated within Monte UGA; this portion is maintained in forest. Outside of UGA, land use is "General Development", which allows residential uses but most parcels are currently in and assumed to remain in forestry through 2040, except along Black Creek. Black & Bitter Creeks have been developed with small residential lots. For roughly 70% of GSU outside UGA, could use SRT 5%.
General Notes: The UGA within this GSU is Montesano's, and falls within the City Forest zone (maintained as forest for city's wellhead protection)

Percent conversion by 2040: 1) Portions of Aberdeen UGA and Cosmopolis within GSU are designated for industrial development. Assume remaining developable land in both UGAs (80% of portion of UGA within GSU, including around Lake Aberdeen) are converted from forested to industrial. 2) In southeast Montesano UGA, assume 50% converted from forest to commercial/industrial. 3) Outside of UGAs, majority of land is in DNR Surge Plain NAP.  Areas outside of the NAP are designated long term ag or already developed; no significant changes in remainder of GSU anticipated by 2040.
General Notes: UGAs in this GSU are for Aberdeen, Hoquiam and SE Montesano. Also includes Lake Aberdeen Park block within City of Aberdeen.
Intensity Assumption: (assume 80% at 0.87,20% at 0.10)*.162 - Chip, this is 80% conversion in one UGA and 50% conversion in another. Both are conversion from forest to commercial/industrial. There is no 20%. I don’t know the area of each UGA, but it apeears to roughly equate to 65% conversion of the total 16.2% of UGA.

Percent conversion by 2040: 1) Within UGA land bank (industrial UGA), assume 30% transition from forest to industrial. 2) outside of 'UGA', convert 10% from forest to residential

Percent conversion by 2040: 1) within Aberdeen UGA, the vast majority is already developed at urban densities. Assume the remainder (about 20% of portion of UGA within GSU) will convert from forest uses to moderate density residential. 2) outside of UGA, about 2/3 of the GSU is designated Agricultural 1 and is not anticipated to convert to other uses in the next ~20 years. The remaining 1/3 of this GSU is designated "General Development", which allows residential uses, however most of the floodplain has already been subdivided and contains rural residential or small to moderate scale farming activities. Potential for other significant conversion within remainder of this GSU in next 20 years is relatively unlikely.
General Notes: UGA is developed portion of Aberdeen. Reach follows the Wishkah up to about Hoquiam Wishkah Road/Nisson.

Percent conversion by 2040: 1) Within the Tumwater UGA in this GSU, the future land use is designated as single family low density and "utilities". Assume 2/3 of this UGA is converted from forest to residential (remaining 1/3 in utilities is currently developed (RRs and power corridors). 2) In rest of GSU, assume 15% converts from forest to residential (most of GSU is the protected Black River).
General Notes: The UGA in this GSU is the SW corner of the City of Tumwater. It includes the Black River and Black Lake, south to about Littlerock Rd/Delphi Rd/110th Ave SW.

Percent conversion by 2040: 1) In Bucoda, land within UGA would be converted from forest to residential. In rest of Thurston Co portion, most land is designated long term ag and forestry, with some rural residential resource (RRR) but is mostly developed. 2) In Centralia UGA, assume conversion from forest to residential. Rest of GSU in Lewis County is mostly developed (mining, residential), some conversion expected in south portion. SUMMARY: 100% of UGA converts from forest to residential, in remainder assume 10% converts from forest to residential.
General Notes: GSU includes far east boundary of Centralia UGA, moving northeast into Thurston County. Includes Bucoda and Skookumchuck River up to the reservoir.

Percent conversion by 2040: 1) within UGA, assume 65% conversion from forest to residential. 2) Development potential in rest of GSU is fair where not already developed. Appear to be many critical areas but some potential. Assume 10% conversion from forest to residential.
